PROJECT PURPOSE


The main purpose of this project is to demonstrate how the heart disease prediction problem can be treated as a supervised machine learning problem using Python and the Scikit-learn toolkit.


For this purpose, we will execute the machine learning cycle.


Heart Disease Prediction System¶

This notebook demonstrates how to build a heart disease prediction system using Python and Scikit-learn.

Assignment Requirements Overview:¶

The assignment involves developing a Heart Disease Prediction System by adapting the code from the Titanic Passenger Survival Prediction System. Key steps include:

  1. Reading and Understanding Provided Lectures
  2. Running the Titanic Code
  3. Adapting the Code for Heart Disease Prediction

Phases of the System¶

The machine learning cycle to be followed:

1. Training Phase:¶

  • Build the model using training data.

2. Testing Phase:¶

  • Evaluate the performance of the model using testing data.

3. Application Phase:¶

  • Deploy the model to predict real-time unseen data.

4. Feedback Phase:¶

  • Collect feedback to improve the model.

Steps to Build Heart Disease Prediction System¶

Step 1: Import Libraries¶

  • Import necessary libraries for data manipulation, visualization, and machine learning.
  • Example: import pandas as pd, import numpy as np, from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, etc.

Step 2: Load the Dataset¶

  • Load the heart disease dataset using pandas.
  • Example: heart_data = pd.read_csv("path/to/heart-disease-dataset.csv")

Step 3: Data Preprocessing¶

  • Handle missing values: Fill or drop missing data as necessary.
  • Encode categorical variables: Use label encoding or one-hot encoding for categorical features.
  • Normalize numerical features: Scale numerical features to a standard range if necessary.

Step 4: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • Visualize the data: Use plots to understand the distribution of features.
  • Correlation analysis: Identify correlations between features and the target variable.

Step 5: Feature Selection¶

  • Select relevant features: Choose features that are most relevant for predicting heart disease.
  • Dimensionality reduction: Use techniques like PCA if necessary to reduce the number of features.

Step 6: Execute the Training Phase¶

  • Split the dataset into training and testing sets.
  • Example: X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

Step 7: Model Selection and Training¶

  • Choose a machine learning model: Select models like Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest, etc.
  • Train the model: Fit the model on the training data.
  • Example: model = LogisticRegression(), model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Step 8: Model Evaluation¶

  • Evaluate the model performance on the test set.
  • Use metrics like accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score.
  • Example: accuracy = model.score(X_test, y_test)

Step 9: Execute the Application Phase¶

  • Take input from user
  • Preprocess the input
  • Save the trained model using joblib or pickle.
  • Load the model and use it to make predictions on new data.
  • Example: import pickle, pickle.dump(model, open("model.pkl", "wb"))

Step 10: Execute the Feedback Phase¶

  • Take feedback from domain experts

Step 11: Improve Model based on Feedback¶

  • Monitor the model performance over time.
  • Update the model with new data periodically.
  • Retrain the model if necessary to maintain accuracy.

Step 12: Additional Model Evaluation and Optimization¶

  • Optimize model performance by tuning hyperparameters using Grid Search or Random Search.
  • Example: from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV, grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, scoring='accuracy', cv=10)

Conclusion¶

  • Building a heart disease prediction system involves several steps from data preprocessing to model deployment.
  • Each step is crucial for building a reliable and accurate prediction system that can assist in early detection and prevention of heart disease.

In [179]:
# Handle Outliers
for feature in numerical_features:
    q1 = heart_data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = heart_data[feature].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    heart_data = heart_data[(heart_data[feature] >= lower_bound) & (heart_data[feature] <= upper_bound)]

Step 5: Feature Selection¶

In [226]:
# Feature Extraction: Select relevant features based on correlation or domain knowledge
selected_features = ['age', 'sex', 'cp', 'trestbps', 'chol', 'thalach', 'exang', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'ca', 'thal']

X = heart_data[selected_features]
y = heart_data['target']

# Splitting the dataset before feature selection
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# Feature selection using Random Forest
model = RandomForestClassifier()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

importances = model.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.title("Feature importances")
plt.bar(range(X_train.shape[1]), importances[indices], align="center")
plt.xticks(range(X_train.shape[1]), [X_train.columns[i] for i in indices], rotation=90)
plt.show()

# Identify top 4 features using Random Forest
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0)
rf_model.fit(X, y)

feature_importances = rf_model.feature_importances_
features = X.columns

importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': features,
    'Importance': feature_importances
}).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

top_4_features = importance_df['Feature'].head(4).tolist()
print("Top 4 Features:", top_4_features)

X_top4 = X[top_4_features]

Top 4 Features: ['thal', 'cp', 'ca', 'thalach']

Explanation of Top 4 Features¶

The top 4 features were selected based on their importance scores from the Random Forest model and their correlation with the target variable (heart disease). These features have the highest predictive power and are crucial for accurate prediction:

  • cp (Chest Pain Type): Highly indicative of heart disease as chest pain is a primary symptom.
  • thal (Thalassemia): Thalassemia conditions can significantly affect heart function.
  • oldpeak (ST Depression Induced by Exercise): Indicates abnormalities in heart function under stress.
  • thalach (Maximum Heart Rate Achieved): Key indicator of cardiovascular health.

# User Input Function
def get_user_input():
    print("Please enter the following details for prediction:")
    user_input = {}
    user_input['age'] = float(input("Age: "))
    user_input['sex'] = int(input("Sex (1 = male, 0 = female): "))
    user_input['cp'] = int(input("Chest Pain Type (0, 1, 2, 3): "))
    user_input['trestbps'] = float(input("Resting Blood Pressure: "))
    user_input['chol'] = float(input("Serum Cholesterol (mg/dl): "))
    user_input['thalach'] = float(input("Maximum Heart Rate Achieved: "))
    user_input['exang'] = int(input("Exercise Induced Angina (1 = yes, 0 = no): "))
    user_input['oldpeak'] = float(input("ST Depression Induced by Exercise: "))
    user_input['slope'] = int(input("Slope of the Peak Exercise ST Segment (0, 1, 2): "))
    user_input['ca'] = int(input("Number of Major Vessels (0-3): "))
    user_input['thal'] = int(input("Thalassemia (1 = normal, 2 = fixed defect, 3 = reversable defect): "))
    return user_input

Step 12: Additional Model Evaluation and Optimization¶

When developing a machine learning model, it's crucial to understand its performance and reliability. This ensures that the model is not only accurate but also generalizes well to new, unseen data. To achieve this, we use various evaluation metrics and optimization techniques. Here’s a brief overview of why we used each approach:

  1. Performance Analysis:

    • Confusion Matrix: Helps us understand the types of errors the model is making by showing the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives.
    • Classification Report: Provides detailed metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score for each class. These metrics help us understand the model's performance in distinguishing between different classes.
    • ROC Curve and AUC: The ROC curve shows the trade-off between sensitivity (recall) and specificity, while the AUC measures the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative classes. These metrics give a holistic view of the model's performance.

  2. Hyperparameter Tuning:

    • Grid Search: Helps us find the best hyperparameters for our SVM model. By systematically searching through a range of hyperparameters, we can identify the combination that gives the best performance.

  3. Cross-Validation:

    • Ensures that our model generalizes well to new data by assessing its performance on different subsets of the dataset. This helps in preventing overfitting.

  4. Try Different Models:

    • Experimenting with different algorithms (like Random Forest, Logistic Regression, KNN) allows us to compare their performance and choose the best one. Different models have different strengths, and some may perform better than others for a given problem.

  5. Ensemble Methods:

    • Bagging with Random Forest: Combines multiple models to improve accuracy. By averaging the predictions of several models, we can reduce variance and improve the overall performance of the model.

  6. Model Reliability:

    • Bootstrap Sampling: Evaluates the reliability of the model by resampling the dataset multiple times and assessing the model's performance on each resampled dataset. This provides an estimate of the model's variability and robustness.

By using these approaches, we can thoroughly evaluate and optimize our heart disease prediction model. This ensures that our model is accurate, reliable, and generalizes well to new data, making it a robust tool for predicting heart disease.

12.3. Cross-Validation¶

  • Use cross-validation to get a more accurate estimate of your model's performance.
  • Cross-validation is used to assess the generalizability of the model.
In [246]:
# Perform cross-validation
cv_scores = cross_val_score(best_model, X, y, cv=5)

# Print cross-validation scores
print("Cross-Validation Scores:", cv_scores)
print("Mean Cross-Validation Score:", cv_scores.mean())
print(f"""The mean cross-validation score of {cv_scores.mean():.2f} indicates that the model's performance is consistent across different subsets of the data.
""")

# Plot Cross-Validation Scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(cv_scores, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b')
plt.title('Cross-Validation Scores')
plt.xlabel('Fold')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.show()

Mean Cross-Validation Score: 0.8362573099415205
The mean cross-validation score of 0.84 indicates that the model's performance is consistent across different subsets of the data.

  • Experiment with other algorithms to see if they perform better.

Trying Different Algorithms¶

In [247]:
# Initialize different models
models = {
    'SVM': best_model,
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0),
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=0),
    'KNN': KNeighborsClassifier()
}

# Evaluate each model
for model_name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)
    print(f"{model_name} Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

12.6. Model Reliability¶

  • Bootstrap sampling provides an estimate of the model's reliability.
  • The mean bootstrap score indicates the average performance of the model over multiple resampled datasets.

Bootstrap Sampling¶

In [248]:
# Number of bootstrap samples
n_iterations = 1000
n_size = int(len(X) * 0.50)

# Run bootstrap
scores = []
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # Prepare train and test sets
    X_resample, y_resample = resample(X, y, n_samples=n_size, random_state=i)
    model.fit(X_resample, y_resample)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)
    scores.append(accuracy)

# Convert scores to a numpy array for convenience
bootstrap_scores = np.array(scores)

# Report performance
print("Bootstrap Scores Mean:", bootstrap_scores.mean())
print("Bootstrap Scores Standard Deviation:", bootstrap_scores.std())

# Plot Bootstrap Scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hist(bootstrap_scores, bins=30, color='c', edgecolor='k', alpha=0.7)
plt.axvline(bootstrap_scores.mean(), color='r', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.title('Bootstrap Scores Distribution')
plt.xlabel('Accuracy')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

Bootstrap Scores Mean: 0.738842105263158
Bootstrap Scores Standard Deviation: 0.06455807581050235

Model Evaluation Summary¶

Explanation of the Code¶

  1. Accuracy Score: Measures the proportion of correctly classified instances among the total instances. It gives a general idea of how well the model performs.

  2. Cross-Validation Scores: Assesses the model's generalizability by splitting the data into different subsets and evaluating the model on each subset. The mean cross-validation score provides an average performance metric across these subsets.

  3. Confusion Matrix: Shows the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives. This helps to understand the types of errors the model is making.

  4. Classification Report: Provides detailed metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score for each class. These metrics give a deeper understanding of the model's performance for each class.

  5. ROC Curve and AUC: The ROC curve shows the trade-off between sensitivity (recall) and specificity. AUC measures the entire two-dimensional area underneath the entire ROC curve, indicating the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative classes.

  6. Bootstrap Scores: Provides an estimate of the model's reliability by resampling the dataset multiple times and evaluating the model on each resampled dataset. The mean bootstrap score indicates the average performance of the model over these resampled datasets.

Visual Representations¶

  1. Cross-Validation Scores Plot: Shows the accuracy for each fold in the cross-validation process.

  2. Confusion Matrix Plot: Visualizes the confusion matrix to understand the distribution of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives.

  3. ROC Curve Plot: Visualizes the ROC curve and the AUC to show the model's performance in distinguishing between classes.

  4. Bootstrap Scores Distribution Plot: Shows the distribution of bootstrap scores to understand the model's reliability.

Conclusion¶

This code snippet provides a comprehensive and understandable summary of the model's performance metrics. It explains what each metric means and includes visual representations to help interpret the results. This approach ensures that even someone without a deep understanding of machine learning can understand how well the model is performing.m
